T1	Participants 259 455	current study aimed to assess the impact of the additional phone calls counselling during the first month on the abstinence rate at 3 and 6 months after quit date among smokers in Penang, Malaysia
T2	Participants 564 661	eligible smokers who attended the clinics between February 1st and October 31st 2012 were invited
T3	Participants 663 930	Participants were randomly assigned by using urn design method either to receive the usual care that followed in the clinics (control) or the usual care procedure plus extra counselling sessions through phone calls during the first month of quit attempt (intervention
T4	Participants 941 1034	Participants in our cohort smoked about 14 cigarettes per day on average (mean = 13.78 ± 7.0)
T5	Participants 1036 1262	At 3 months, control group was less likely to quit smoking compared to intervention group (36.9% vs. 46.7%, verified smoking status) but this did not reach statistical significance (OR = 0.669; 95% CI = 0.395-1.133, P = 0.86).
T6	Participants 1272 1424	at 6 months, 71.7% of the intervention group were successfully quit smoking (bio-chemically verified) compared to 48.6% of the control group (P < 0.001)
T7	Participants 1426 1536	The control group were significantly less likely to quit smoking (OR = 0.375; 95% CI = 0.217-0.645, P < 0.001)
